I don't know the character limit for this response, but I'm sure it's not even close to enough to truly answer this question. Having done my undergrad here and currently in my grad degree, I have seen firsthand just how little student well-being is ever considered. Actually addressing the issue would necessarily require a radical restructuring to bring student well-being from a fringe concern to a central, organizing focus.
To start, I would kindly suggest getting Purdue Engineering's head out of its ass. The fanciful notions of how "great" the College is is far removed from the actual state of affairs and detrimental to the possibility of progress. There's a lot to be done, but you can't do any of it until you accept the true extent of the problem. 

And also, for the love of God, get rid of all this GRIT nonsense already. The academic literature in psychology abandoned the concept of "grit" many years ago, for good reasons.

Q2: Purdue Student Organizations have been an integral part of my personal well-being. They have given me an outlet for stress and a way to make friends, which has been extremely important for me.
Q3: Although staff and professors say they care about mental health, the realities of the classes do not support mental health most of the time. So many students in engineering are getting very little sleep because they are just trying to finish everything they need to. Some of this may be due in part to a lack of thorough instruction on homework topics, which forces students to spend more time on each task because they have to learn everything better than it was taught to them. Thus, I think that all Purdue Engineering professors should be thorough in their teaching instead of leaving it mostly up to the students to do in their free time in addition to the homework.

Communication within the department could be improved. This semester I am taking three courses required for my ChemE degree, two of which are in the ChemE department. The homework for all three classes is due Friday at 9:00 AM, 11:30 AM, and 4 PM. This causes a lot of stress, especially on Thursday nights. I frequently don't go to sleep until the early hours of Friday morning each week. This would not be so much an issue if I didn't have other homework that has to also be completed earlier throughout the week. 
Additionally, late required PSOs do not pair well with student life. I have not been able to  participate in several club events due to evening PSOs. I have a PSO Tuesday evening 6:30-8:30 that is a combo recitation and lab, with the lab being due that night at 11:59 PM. 
Finally, this semester my two ChemE classes scheduled their second midterms on the same day. This could have been avoided if there was better communication within the department. Exams, especially in technically focused courses are very mentally draining, and having to take two in one day will not allow me to do my absolute best on both exams.

Q3: Consider people’s motivation when they have free time. There’s two types of free time: time off, and actual free time. Time off is time where a student doesn’t have to be doing anything school or work related. Time off doesn’t usually contain motivation to do things you are passionate about or interested in pursuing. Free time has that motivation to expand oneself. I feel that most of what happens here in Purdue Engineering is time off rather than free time because students are so drained with stressful projects, challenging subjects, and exams. We aren’t robots that are being programmed to be the ideal engineers. We are people, human beings, and when all of our motivation is drained by school, it makes it nearly impossible for us to be creative in our own way and express ourselves. If you want quality, unique work, don’t expect people to complete a project the same way as everybody else in a week. Focus more on individual people using their unique abilities and experiences to develop new ideas that will help progress our modern world, not maintain it by doing the same thing as everybody else. Gives us time to be ourselves and use our skills to benefit the world like aspiring engineers should be doing.

Purdue engineering needs to relax on the amount of work that they expect students to do. I understand that this is a STEM school, but I feel that if students truly want to succeed in the classroom to the best of their abilities, there is not time to do anything else besides studying.

I have had so many classes that I did not actively know what my grade at the end of the semester would be because I didn't know what kind of curve would be put on it at the end. It seems to me like it would make more sense to have a reasonable amount of out of class work and reasonable exams that actively reflect the material being taught in class such that it would not be necessary to have such extreme curves.

Q3: Having classes where grades reflect the work that is done and where classes that are generally taken in the same semester coordinate so that not all homework assignments are due on the same night each week. Get rid of the mentality that the average on an exam was too high and accept the idea that students may have learned material applicable to the exam from the teaching that the professor did. pandemic: Having recorded lectures also posted online. Sure students are still going to miss class in ways they did pre-pandemic but in a pandemic/"post-pandemic world" we're seeing students miss class more in order to make sure they don't have covid, being burnt out quicker, general illness that feels stronger than before, etc. And professors already reuse content so we know that they have their recorded lectures from previous semesters so why not post it as a supplement? Especially for classes where the professor outright tells their students that the textbook is incorrect in many spots. Also I would really appreciate seeing the same urgency getting content posted now like we had last year. Most professors have either slacked off or severely slacked off (I can very clearly name this professor but I will not) and it's only making the overall situation worse for students as we try to adjust in to a so-called "normal times" when things clearly aren't normal and in fact worse off then before. This all really makes it hard to feel like our departments/professors/advisors care since they only tell us that *insert course* is supposed to be hard. I'm sorry but a hard course doesn't excuse poor management

I only say this because, while there's always going to be complains, seeing the number of students dissatisfied by their professors/departments/Purdue is alarmingly high this semester in my opinion and we don't know how to get effective change rolling when departments aren't making drastic enough moves to make professors either understand or change. Hence why I mention incentives since it's just human nature to work for awards or to avoid negative attention

Make better, more robust assumptions about your students. We don't all have access to cameras remote to our screens, we don't all have printers by our sides, not all of us can use gradescope properly on our phones.

Look, I know that assumptions have to be made, but in the case of the ones made during the pandemic, I got a strong sense that they were made out of convenience of the policy makers rather than the likelyhood of it being correct. You seriously don't know what it's like to try and take an exam when your screen is bent over so the camera can actually see your hands as required. I'd LOVE to have enough time to dedicate 3+ hours to writing but after a number crunch that is literally never ending, night after night. I don't really have that energy. This is not the case for all of my classes. ME430 is still virtual but all the material is written in synchronous lectures and the professor genuinely cares about his students. To contrast this, ME 363 uses recycled material, has a major disconnect between the professor and students, no clear communication for the class, then they wonder why the average on an exam was a 50%. No.  FYE was a miserable experience.  You made it even worse during the pandemic.  You refused to extend the 4 semester cut off date for FYE students to declare a major despite having an entire semester, debatably 2, wasted from the pandemic.  I had to retake Chem 2 since the transition to online was not handled well and it became impossible for me to keep up with the course work due to my ADHD. Online classes were a bad joke. I don’t feel I learned anything from taking online courses, cause again, I don’t learn will with online courses due to my ADHD.  And honestly, I talked to people without a disability and they said they just stopped logging into lectures since they weren’t getting anything out of it.  
The entire FYE experience has been miserable for me.  I debated dropping out several times.  If I did not have an internship at an engineering firm prior to coming to Purdue I might have left the engineering program. 
But hey at least I’m used to feeling overworked and super anxious about everything now so if that’s what your Goal was congratulations.
Q2: No, I haven’t had time to join an organization due to all of the work I have to get done in a week.  I’m finally starting to go to the gym regularly and I’m a junior.
Q3:
I honestly have no idea.  For a start, make FYE related more to engineering and less about pointless busy work for the first half, and then surprising students with assignments they weren’t given the skills to complete.  Engr 132 was admittedly a better experience than 131, but I struggled with understanding programming so I struggled more in that class.  After retaking 132 I had a much better experience, especially thanks to having a great group that helped me work through problems.

  Engr 131 sucked since we had lectures, full lectures, where nothing of substance was said.  We were given assignments in excel for the first half or 3/4ths of the class without any real instructions on how to use the features we were supposed to use for assignments.  We had a lot of time for “sharing” and “teamwork exercises” tho.  Which were fine for the first day, fun even.  But we had like the first week, maybe 2 weeks, where it was just the same stuff: “you’re all valued”, “you’re all special”, “diversity strengthens the engineering field”.  Yes, I agree with all of that, but how do I use excel?  I was constantly on Microsoft support pages looking up how to do certain functions.  But my “favorite” part was when we were given a group project that required us to do programming we weren’t taught, wiring we learned about in one lecture, and to make a full model.

  In that projects defense, I would have enjoyed it more if the entire 131 class led up to it.  Like we had a unit on programming, a unit on wiring, a unit on model-building, ect, that culminated in the final project.  The biggest reasons I didn’t like the project was because I wasn’t given the resources to feel I was a valuable member of the group.  The other 3 people already knew how to do most of the stuff for our projects, but I was the odd man out who couldn’t do anything right.  It sucked man.  Really a kick in the self-confidence balls.  I was given a project I normally would have loved, but was not given the skills to complete it to an extent I was proud of, and felt like I was constantly holding the group back.

  Sorry if I’m ranting a bit, this survey has dug up some old wounds I think.  I heard from some freshman in my physics class that FYE was even worse during the pandemic.  All 3 of them were women in my lab group who were planning on being engineers.  Two switched out of engineering cause they couldn’t deal with the stress from the work-load from among all their classes (not just engineering department, but the classes required for FYE students as well).  One switched out mid semester cause she was just so miserable.  The both liked engineering, but yea they’re doing something else now.

Hire more mental health professionals for your Push therapy thing as well.  Me and another friend of mine were/are debating seeing a therapist but our other friend mentioned to us the waiting time for a Purdue therapist can be over a year.  Like, guys, that’s unacceptable

Q2: Student organizations are great resources to improve your resume and academic skills outside of class, but they are also great places to meet new people. I’ve made lots of friends in student organizations and even met my girlfriend at one. It’s really nice to meet people with similar passions and build a network of friends.
Q3: I think the biggest detriment to student well being is also one of the biggest advantages to going to Purdue: the challenging work. While homework and exams can be very stressful and lead to terrible sleep schedules, it’s also the hard work that makes a Purdue degree so valuable. I think to help balance this, there could be clearer guidelines for professors when it comes to workloads and exams. I have a few classes with more work than necessary and other classes that assign lengthy homework over breaks or during the week of an exam. More awareness to students total workload (across all classes) and ability to balance multiple difficult classes at once would go a long way in improving mental health and overall well being.

a) Increase wage for TAs and graders. The wage of TAs and graders is lower than local restaurants and cafeterias, many of which is currently seeking new employment due to the loss of older employment in covid-19. 
b) Increase the amount of TAs and graders, which is hard to achieve unless (a) is satisfied. I know a ECE TA who told me that he has been put in a hard situation because he must handle three things at once: his job as a TA, which he seek to drop but wasn't able to once he enrolled, his graduate classes, and his research. He had to drop his research at the end of the day. A very similar situation happened to one of my introductory class, where the instructor is also a grad student and became exhausted in the exact same position. 
c) I checked an online list of annual salary list at Purdue (Purdue has been posting wages of its faculty and staff as an public university). I found that Purdue seems to be reducing many professor's wages in 2020. However, Purdue hired a few new sports coaches and a few administrative personnel that are paid much higher than faculty members, in a few cases, the newly hired has one or two million dollars in salary in 2020. ( Data from https://openpayrolls.com/rank/highest-paid-employees/purdue-university). With my observation that one of my class does not have a TA, I do not think it is good to the university health in mid to long term.

Q3: I am unsure what Purdue Engineering can do to improve student well-being, though sometimes I wonder why exams are made such big portions of the overall grades of certain classes; as mentioned before I don't do anything but schoolwork, and I can spend hours studying for a test only to still mess up and not do the best on it. I'm sure that many others have tried their best to keep their grades up, only for something to happen and they lose what they have been working so very hard for. This can be especially the case with Final Exams. I really doubt that anyone wants to forget what they have learned, and sometimes there are people like me who for some reason forget easily even when not being distracted by other things. I do understand that there are people who don't put in all of the effort required, but I'm sure that most students do care and are trying their best despite what certain grades they receive might imply. Perhaps this is not so much an issue with Purdue as much as it is an issue with the world itself; plenty of people try their hardest but don't get what some might assume they deserve for all of their hard work in return. I should probably stop talking about this, as it is just making me feel sad and I still have so much to do before the semester ends.
